<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,314,964,987]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">FIGURES 6–8.</emphasis>
Genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authority="Prosvirov, 2017" authorityName="Prosvirov" authorityYear="2017" box="[447,656,964,985]" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Hypnoidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afghanus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[447,656,964,985]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Hypnoidus afghanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[662,768,964,986]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[662,743,965,986]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
6.
</emphasis>
Holotype, aedeagus, ventral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1124,1144,965,986]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">7.</emphasis>
Paratype, ovipositor, ventral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[211,230,995,1016]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">8.</emphasis>
Paratype, part of female genital tract, general view. Not to scale.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
Scutellum flat, about as long as wide, truncated at anterior margin, with sparse small punctures. Both elytra together ellipsoidal, slightly wider than pronotum, widest behind middle, more than twice as long as pronotum (both elytra together: length 
<quantity box="[489,583,1129,1153]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" unit="mm" value="4.3">4.3 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[674,769,1129,1153]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
); tapering more strongly to apex than to base; shoulders obtusely rounded. Disc of elytra flat, elytral striae near suture with fine circular punctures; lateral striae with larger and deeper punctures; each interstria with two or three rows of fine, sparse punctures. Wings strongly reduced, represented by vestigials at basal parts of elytra.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,316,1272,1297]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Abdomen punctate as metasternum. Ratio of length of abdominal sternite 2 and length of metasternum about 0.5.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,311,1344,1369]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Aedeagus</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[327,394,1344,1369]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,964,987]" captionTargetBox="[360,1239,188,919]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[340,1247,183,953]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 8. Genitalia of Hypnoidus afghanus sp. nov. 6. Holotype, aedeagus, ventral view. 7. Paratype, ovipositor, ventral view. 8. Paratype, part of female genital tract, general view. Not to scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/898846/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Parameres about as long as penis, almost straight, expanded at anterior quarter, rounded at apex. Penis rather slender, somewhat narrow, its apophysis short, about 0.3 times as long as penis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,1416,1441]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[301,407,1416,1441]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1958,1981]" captionTargetBox="[281,1318,515,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[268,1327,505,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Habitus of Hypnoidus afghanus sp. nov., dorsal (Figs. 1, 2), ventral (Fig. 3) and lateral (Figs. 4, 5) view. 1, 3, 4. Male, holotype (6.3 mm). 2, 5. Female, paratype (6.8 mm). Not to scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/898844/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Figs. 2, 5</figureCitation>
). Coloration lighter than in male. Body larger than in male (length 
<quantity box="[1162,1251,1416,1441]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.8" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" unit="mm" value="6.8">6.8 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[1333,1424,1417,1441]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" unit="mm" value="2.3">2.3 mm</quantity>
); disc of pronotum more convex, without median impession. Antenna shorter than in male. In all other respects similar to male.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,396,1524,1549]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[413,523,1524,1549]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,964,987]" captionTargetBox="[360,1239,188,919]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[340,1247,183,953]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 8. Genitalia of Hypnoidus afghanus sp. nov. 6. Holotype, aedeagus, ventral view. 7. Paratype, ovipositor, ventral view. 8. Paratype, part of female genital tract, general view. Not to scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/898846/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Figs. 7, 8</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor rather long; baculum long, weakly sclerotized (length of baculum/ length of ovipositor 0.8); coxite weakly sclerotized, narrowed to apex, with short, indistinct stylus, and with several setae. Bursa copulatrix without sclerotized structures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" box="[199,399,1632,1657]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,274,1633,1656]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Larva.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="272" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" box="[199,988,1668,1693]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1668,1693]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Distribution.</emphasis>
Northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[511,652,1668,1693]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
: Hindu Kush mountain range.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,330,1704,1729]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Bionomics.</emphasis>
The biology of this species remains unknown, but according to its morphological characters (almost complete reduction of wings and associated shortening of metasternum) and the label data it is likely that 
<taxonomicName authority="Prosvirov, 2017" authorityName="Prosvirov" authorityYear="2017" box="[151,288,1776,1800]" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Hypnoidus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afghanus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,288,1776,1800]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">H. afghanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[295,384,1776,1801]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[295,384,1776,1801]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
lives exclusively in high mountain areas.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1412,1812,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1056,1837]" box="[199,1412,1812,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1812,1837]" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the new species is derived from the name of the country of its origin, 
<collectingCountry box="[1267,1407,1812,1837]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="3" pageNumber="272">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
